    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-05-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-05-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="316"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d316">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <gloss target="#t_UNP1">UNP</gloss> files, lot 59 D 237, “Slates”</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Acting Director of the Office of United
                        Nations Political and Security Affairs</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_POPPERDH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Popper</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Assistant Secretary of State for United
                        Nations Affairs</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_KEYDMK1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Key</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-05-19">May 19,
                            1954</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <item>Subject:</item>
                    <item>Attached Cable on <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> Elections</item>
                </list>
                <p>Pursuant to a conversation with Mr. <persName corresp="#p_WAINHOUSEDW1"
                        >Wainhouse</persName>, we have drafted the attached interim reply<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d316fn1">See Department’s telegram 567, May 19, to New York, <hi
                            rend="italic">infra</hi>,</note> to the two cables from New York on the
                        <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss> Presidency and the <gloss target="#t_SC1"
                        >SC</gloss> election. The reply expresses the belief we should keep our
                    position flexible for the moment particularly in view of Indochina and
                    Geneva.</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_EUR1">EUR</gloss> has cleared the cable. Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_DRUMRIGHTEF1">Drumright</persName>,<note n="2" xml:id="d316fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_DRUMRIGHTEF1">Everett F. Drumright</persName>, Deputy
                        Assistant Secretary of State for Far Eastern Affairs.</note> however, does
                    not concur on the grounds that our reply should take cognizance of the arguments
                    advanced in the two cables from New York<note n="3" xml:id="d316fn3">Presumably
                            <gloss target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss>’s telegram 678, Apr. 30, 6 p.m.,
                        and telegram 732, May 17, 6 p.m., <ref target="#pg_535">p. 535</ref> and <hi
                            rend="italic">supra</hi>, respectively.</note> and that the Department
                    should reach a decision without further delay on the elections in question.</p>
                <p>We suggest that you discuss the problem with Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_DRUMRIGHTEF1">Drumright</persName> and, if necessary, with Mr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_MURPHYRD1">Murphy</persName>, to try to obtain
                    Departmental agreement on the cable.</p>
            </div>
